And JIT compilation means that
app installs are much faster--

01:09:58.490 --> 01:10:02.600
75% faster in N. So now
users can get up and running

01:10:02.600 --> 01:10:06.130
in your apps much more quickly.

01:10:06.130 --> 01:10:09.280
And also because JIT is more
selective about which methods

01:10:09.280 --> 01:10:11.250
it compiles, we're
also able to reduce

01:10:11.250 --> 01:10:16.590
the amount of storage unit
for app code by a full 50%.

01:10:16.590 --> 01:10:19.070
Now, unlike conventional
JIT systems,

01:10:19.070 --> 01:10:22.380
the Android runtime uses
profile-guided optimization

01:10:22.380 --> 01:10:24.800
to write compiled code to
flash for the next time you

01:10:24.800 --> 01:10:25.900
run the app.

01:10:25.900 --> 01:10:29.890
So this improves performance
and reduces battery consumption.

01:10:29.890 --> 01:10:33.950
In summary, the new JIT compiler
improves software performance,

01:10:33.950 --> 01:10:37.090
makes installs faster, and
reduces the amount of storage

01:10:37.090 --> 01:10:40.450
you need for apps
on your device.

01:10:40.450 --> 01:10:43.090
Let's talk about another
big area of focus for us--

01:10:43.090 --> 01:10:44.630
security.

01:10:44.630 --> 01:10:46.540
We designed Android
from the beginning

01:10:46.540 --> 01:10:50.830
with a multi-layered, defense
in depth security architecture.

01:10:50.830 --> 01:10:53.950
And Android employs the
latest cutting-edge security

01:10:53.950 --> 01:10:56.800
technologies, things
like SE Linux,

01:10:56.800 --> 01:11:00.360
verified boot integrity,
and full disk encryption.

01:11:00.360 --> 01:11:03.340
With N, we're continuing
to strengthen our defenses

01:11:03.340 --> 01:11:05.440
in three key ways.

01:11:05.440 --> 01:11:09.120
First, N introduces
file-based encryption.

01:11:09.120 --> 01:11:12.560
By encrypting at the file level
instead of the block level,

01:11:12.560 --> 01:11:14.940
we're able to better
isolate and protect

01:11:14.940 --> 01:11:17.870
individual users of the system.

01:11:17.870 --> 01:11:20.190
Second, we learned the
importance last year

01:11:20.190 --> 01:11:23.470
of hardening the security
of the media framework,

01:11:23.470 --> 01:11:25.300
especially since
it's accessing files

01:11:25.300 --> 01:11:27.160
from anywhere on the internet.

01:11:27.160 --> 01:11:30.310
So in N, we've split
out key subsystems

01:11:30.310 --> 01:11:34.630
into individual SE Linux
protected processes,

01:11:34.630 --> 01:11:37.280
things like codex
and file extractors.

01:11:37.280 --> 01:11:39.650
By improving the security
of the media framework,

01:11:39.650 --> 01:11:42.950
we improve the security
of the entire device.

01:11:42.950 --> 01:11:44.490
Third-- and this
is something that's

01:11:44.490 --> 01:11:47.890
really cool-- N automatically
keeps your phone up

01:11:47.890 --> 01:11:51.050
to date with the latest
version of the system software

01:11:51.050 --> 01:11:54.210
without you having
to do anything.

01:11:54.210 --> 01:11:57.710
LIke Chromebooks, new
Android devices built on N

01:11:57.710 --> 01:12:01.150
have two system images.

01:12:01.150 --> 01:12:03.340
So when an update is
available, your phone

01:12:03.340 --> 01:12:06.120
will automatically download
the new system image

01:12:06.120 --> 01:12:07.490
in the background.

01:12:07.490 --> 01:12:09.390
So the next time you
power up your phone,

01:12:09.390 --> 01:12:12.974
it will seamlessly switch
into the new software image.

01:12:12.974 --> 01:12:14.640
You're no longer asked
for your password

01:12:14.640 --> 01:12:17.500
when the phone powers up,
thanks to file-based encryption

01:12:17.500 --> 01:12:20.280
and a new feature
called direct boot.

01:12:20.280 --> 01:12:22.380
And that pesky
Android is Upgrading

01:12:22.380 --> 01:12:25.957
dialog is finally gone, thanks
to the new JIT compiler.

01:12:25.957 --> 01:12:29.310
[APPLAUSE]

01:12:31.169 --> 01:12:33.210
I think the best feeling
in the software industry

01:12:33.210 --> 01:12:36.296
is actually deleting
code, by the way.

01:12:36.296 --> 01:12:37.670
This approach to
software updates

01:12:37.670 --> 01:12:39.720
is one of the most loved
features of Chromebooks.

01:12:39.720 --> 01:12:42.810
And I'm really excited to
bring it to mobile as well.

01:12:42.810 --> 01:12:45.470
So that's some of the ways we're
improving security mechanisms

01:12:45.470 --> 01:12:46.770
in the platform.

01:12:46.770 --> 01:12:49.240
But let's not forget about
all of the security services

01:12:49.240 --> 01:12:53.480
that Google provides to keep
all Android devices safe.

01:12:53.480 --> 01:12:56.800
In fact, when you think about
the scale of Android and Google

01:12:56.800 --> 01:13:00.220
Play and the number of
devices and apps out there,

01:13:00.220 --> 01:13:03.830
we're providing one of the most
comprehensive mobile security

01:13:03.830 --> 01:13:06.200
solutions in the world.

01:13:06.200 --> 01:13:08.480
Let's take a look
at a few examples.

01:13:08.480 --> 01:13:10.350
Google Chrome
protects users when

01:13:10.350 --> 01:13:14.310
they're surfing the web through
a system called Safe Browsing.

01:13:14.310 --> 01:13:16.940
Safe Browsing warns
users ahead of time

01:13:16.940 --> 01:13:18.470
when they're about
to go to a site

01:13:18.470 --> 01:13:22.940
that we know contains malware
or is known to be deceptive.

01:13:22.940 --> 01:13:27.680
Today, we're protecting over
one billion mobile Chrome users.

01:13:27.680 --> 01:13:29.920
Another example of
how we protect users

01:13:29.920 --> 01:13:32.350
is through the
Google Play store.

01:13:32.350 --> 01:13:35.980
All Android apps undergo
rigorous security testing

01:13:35.980 --> 01:13:38.450
before appearing on the store.

01:13:38.450 --> 01:13:42.510
We review every app to make
sure it meets our policies.

01:13:42.510 --> 01:13:45.540
We also run an app security
improvement program

01:13:45.540 --> 01:13:48.650
with developers to
identify potential security

01:13:48.650 --> 01:13:49.930
vulnerabilities.

01:13:49.930 --> 01:13:52.440
For example, we've worked with
key banking and e-commerce

01:13:52.440 --> 01:13:55.930
applications to ensure
they're using HTTPS properly

01:13:55.930 --> 01:13:59.200
to protect against man
in the middle attacks.

01:13:59.200 --> 01:14:02.560
Google Play itself is
built on a state of the art

01:14:02.560 --> 01:14:07.260
cloud-based infrastructure
we called Safety Net.

01:14:07.260 --> 01:14:10.090
With Safety Net, Google's expert
systems and machine learning

01:14:10.090 --> 01:14:13.110
models analyze billions
of signals every day

01:14:13.110 --> 01:14:15.070
to predict bad behavior.

01:14:15.070 --> 01:14:17.490
If an app steps out
of line, Google Play

01:14:17.490 --> 01:14:20.510
will block or uninstall
the app, no matter

01:14:20.510 --> 01:14:22.710
where it was installed from.

01:14:22.710 --> 01:14:25.700
And the scale of Safety
Net is extraordinary.

01:14:25.700 --> 01:14:29.860
Every day, we test
over a billion devices

01:14:29.860 --> 01:14:33.060
and over eight billion
installed apps.

01:14:33.060 --> 01:14:34.940
And all of this
happens under the hood

01:14:34.940 --> 01:14:38.200
to keep you safe and secure, no
matter what version of Android

01:14:38.200 --> 01:14:40.160
you're on.

01:14:40.160 --> 01:14:41.650
Let's move on.

01:14:41.650 --> 01:14:45.030
A third area of focus for
us is our continued effort

01:14:45.030 --> 01:14:47.100
to improve productivity.

01:14:47.100 --> 01:14:50.910
And we've taken a close look at
how people multitask on Android

01:14:50.910 --> 01:14:53.080
to understand what's
working for them

01:14:53.080 --> 01:14:55.060
and where we could improve.

01:14:55.060 --> 01:14:58.660
And we've particularly focused
on the recent Apps screen.

01:14:58.660 --> 01:15:00.410
And what we learned
from our user research

01:15:00.410 --> 01:15:03.500
is that over 99% of
the time, people only

01:15:03.500 --> 01:15:06.830
select an app within
the last seven.

01:15:06.830 --> 01:15:10.310
So we decided to simplify by
automatically removing apps

01:15:10.310 --> 01:15:12.980
in the list that you
haven't used in a while.

01:15:12.980 --> 01:15:15.400
This that makes it much
easier to find the app

01:15:15.400 --> 01:15:17.010
that you're looking for.

01:15:17.010 --> 01:15:19.690
Also, based on popular
demand, we finally

01:15:19.690 --> 01:15:21.470
added a Clear All
button at the top.

01:15:24.010 --> 01:15:27.000
Yeah, feels good.

01:15:27.000 --> 01:15:29.570
But my absolute favorite
feature is something

01:15:29.570 --> 01:15:31.490
that we call Quick Switch.

01:15:31.490 --> 01:15:35.000
You can now flip to the previous
app you were in just by double

01:15:35.000 --> 01:15:37.690
tapping the Recents
button from anywhere.

01:15:37.690 --> 01:15:40.950
You can think of it like
a simplified Alt Tab.

01:15:40.950 --> 01:15:43.570
And it's amazingly useful
in so many situations.

01:15:43.570 --> 01:15:45.500
For example, let's say
I'm in a phone call

01:15:45.500 --> 01:15:47.550
and I'm trying to
coordinate an event.

01:15:47.550 --> 01:15:49.380
I can flip over to
the calendar app

01:15:49.380 --> 01:15:51.880
I was just in by double
tapping the Recents

01:15:51.880 --> 01:15:53.430
button at the bottom right.

01:15:53.430 --> 01:15:55.270
From there, I can
check my schedule

01:15:55.270 --> 01:15:58.060
and then flip back to the dialer
by double tapping the Recents

01:15:58.060 --> 01:15:58.900
button again.

01:15:58.900 --> 01:16:00.410
It's pretty cool.

01:16:00.410 --> 01:16:03.380
Now, many of you also
asked for the ability

01:16:03.380 --> 01:16:06.440
to display more than one
app at the same time.

01:16:06.440 --> 01:16:08.370
So we've invested
a lot of effort

01:16:08.370 --> 01:16:12.130
in redesigning our window
management framework in N.

01:16:12.130 --> 01:16:14.960
And we're introducing two
powerful new windowing

01:16:14.960 --> 01:16:19.910
modes in this release-- split
screen and picture in picture.

01:16:19.910 --> 01:16:23.100
Split screen is designed
for tablets and phones,

01:16:23.100 --> 01:16:24.940
and it's really simple to use.

01:16:24.940 --> 01:16:28.480
So for example, let's say
I'm watching a video YouTube

01:16:28.480 --> 01:16:31.360
to learn how to make
the best nachos.

01:16:31.360 --> 01:16:34.980
I can long tap on the Recents
button to enter Multi Window

01:16:34.980 --> 01:16:37.860
and from there launch something
like Google Keep, for example.

01:16:37.860 --> 01:16:40.230
Now I can update my shopping
list for ingredients

01:16:40.230 --> 01:16:42.760
while I'm watching the video.

01:16:42.760 --> 01:16:45.000
The second mode,
picture in picture,

01:16:45.000 --> 01:16:47.070
is designed for Android TV.

01:16:47.070 --> 01:16:49.770
And it's a great way to let
you keep watching something

01:16:49.770 --> 01:16:52.290
while you perform another task.

01:16:52.290 --> 01:16:55.010
For example, let's say I'm
watching a live TV program

01:16:55.010 --> 01:16:57.544
on retro gaming and they're
talking about "Pac-Man."

01:16:57.544 --> 01:16:59.710
And I want to see if I can
install and play the game

01:16:59.710 --> 01:17:00.770
myself.

01:17:00.770 --> 01:17:04.200
I can put the live content into
picture in picture mode to keep

01:17:04.200 --> 01:17:07.440
watching it and then go ahead
and perform a voice search

01:17:07.440 --> 01:17:08.820
for "Pac-Man."

01:17:08.820 --> 01:17:11.040
This will then give me an
option to install the game

01:17:11.040 --> 01:17:13.630
from the Play Store, all at
the same time as watching

01:17:13.630 --> 01:17:14.420
the content.

01:17:14.420 --> 01:17:17.130
It's pretty cool.

01:17:17.130 --> 01:17:19.520
Notifications is
another area we've

01:17:19.520 --> 01:17:22.590
worked on to improve
productivity in Android.

01:17:22.590 --> 01:17:25.410
And it turns out that today,
over half of the notifications

01:17:25.410 --> 01:17:28.910
shown on Android originated
from messaging applications.

01:17:28.910 --> 01:17:32.190
So we decided to make some
changes to really optimize

01:17:32.190 --> 01:17:33.860
for this use case.

01:17:33.860 --> 01:17:37.960
We've added a new direct reply
feature, which lets you quickly

01:17:37.960 --> 01:17:41.110
reply to a message like so.

01:17:41.110 --> 01:17:42.960
You no longer need
to launch the app

01:17:42.960 --> 01:17:46.410
to fire off a quick response,
so it's a real time saver.

01:17:46.410 --> 01:17:48.660
We've also added a
feature to give you more

01:17:48.660 --> 01:17:50.600
control over notifications.

01:17:50.600 --> 01:17:53.260
With N, you can long
tap a notification

01:17:53.260 --> 01:17:55.170
to change its visibility.

01:17:55.170 --> 01:17:58.340
For example, you can block
notifications from a given app

01:17:58.340 --> 01:18:00.800
or set them to
show only silently.

01:18:00.800 --> 01:18:04.060
So now you're able to
choose which notifications

01:18:04.060 --> 01:18:06.240
are important for you.

01:18:06.240 --> 01:18:09.140
One other area we've worked on
to improve your productivity

01:18:09.140 --> 01:18:12.850
in Android is your ability to
express yourself with emoji.

01:18:12.850 --> 01:18:15.150
And Android is the
first mobile platform

01:18:15.150 --> 01:18:20.420
to support the new
Unicode 9 emoji standard.

01:18:20.420 --> 01:18:22.520
With this edition are
more human-looking

01:18:22.520 --> 01:18:25.470
glyphs and support for
skin tone variations.

01:18:25.470 --> 01:18:29.935
Unicode 9 also brings
72 new emoji glyphs.

01:18:29.935 --> 01:18:32.060
So now, you can let your
friends know, for example,

01:18:32.060 --> 01:18:34.130
when you're dancing
like the left shark

01:18:34.130 --> 01:18:36.060
while juggling and
eating avocado toast

01:18:36.060 --> 01:18:39.330
in order to win first prize
in that selfie contest.

01:18:39.330 --> 01:18:42.700
Basically, my typical
Friday night-- not.

01:18:42.700 --> 01:18:45.530
But more seriously, we're
really committed to this space.

01:18:45.530 --> 01:18:48.450
And we're continuing to
work with Unicode consortium

01:18:48.450 --> 01:18:51.490
on the next generation of emoji.

01:18:51.490 --> 01:18:54.170
In particular, you may have
seen some of our suggestions

01:18:54.170 --> 01:18:57.080
around better representing
women in professional roles.

01:18:57.080 --> 01:18:59.288
So thank you for all the
support for apps so far.

01:19:05.150 --> 01:19:06.750
All right, let's wrap up.

01:19:06.750 --> 01:19:09.370
Android N is the best
version of Android yet.

01:19:09.370 --> 01:19:11.950
I have to say that,
but it's actually true.

01:19:11.950 --> 01:19:14.410
We made it faster
and more performance,

01:19:14.410 --> 01:19:16.870
with the powerful new JIT
compiler and Vulkan 3D

01:19:16.870 --> 01:19:17.810
graphics.

01:19:17.810 --> 01:19:20.510
We're continuing to
harden our security

01:19:20.510 --> 01:19:23.510
and provide the first truly
seamless software update

01:19:23.510 --> 01:19:24.555
system for mobile.

01:19:24.555 --> 01:19:27.300
And we're making
users more productive,

01:19:27.300 --> 01:19:30.230
with better multitasking,
brand-new Multi Windows

01:19:30.230 --> 01:19:33.020
support, and improved
notifications.

01:19:33.020 --> 01:19:36.580
In fact, there are over
250 major new features

01:19:36.580 --> 01:19:39.340
in N, everything from
Java 8 language support,

01:19:39.340 --> 01:19:42.520
[INAUDIBLE] to Data Saver,
setting suggestions,

01:19:42.520 --> 01:19:44.080
and much, much more.

01:19:44.080 --> 01:19:46.660
You can check out the What's
New in Android session

01:19:46.660 --> 01:19:49.829
later today to learn even more.

01:19:49.829 --> 01:19:52.120
We're still putting the final
touches on the N release,

01:19:52.120 --> 01:19:54.930
and we expect to launch
it later this summer.

01:19:54.930 --> 01:19:56.587
But if you can't
wait until then,

01:19:56.587 --> 01:19:58.170
I'm happy today to
announce that we're

01:19:58.170 --> 01:20:00.290
publishing our first
beta quality release

01:20:00.290 --> 01:20:03.625
candidate for you to try out
on your main phone or tablet.

01:20:07.830 --> 01:20:12.170
Opt in to the new beta program
at www.android.com/beta and run

01:20:12.170 --> 01:20:18.040
N on your Nexus 6, 9, 5x, 6P,
Nexus Player, and Pixel C. Now,

01:20:18.040 --> 01:20:21.300
there's one more area in N that
we've been working hard on that

01:20:21.300 --> 01:20:23.080
we haven't talked about yet.

01:20:23.080 --> 01:20:25.140
And to tell you more
about what it is

01:20:25.140 --> 01:20:27.550
and how it fits into
our bigger plans,

01:20:27.550 --> 01:20:29.500
let me invite up Clay Bavor.

01:20:29.500 --> 01:20:30.050
Thank you.

01:20:38.798 --> 01:20:40.450
CLAY BAVOR: Thank you, Dave.

01:20:40.450 --> 01:20:41.610
I'm Clay Bavor.

01:20:41.610 --> 01:20:44.650
And I lead the virtual
reality team at Google.

01:20:44.650 --> 01:20:48.640
[APPLAUSE]

01:20:48.640 --> 01:20:50.980
And just to get right
to it, virtual reality

01:20:50.980 --> 01:20:55.420
is coming to
Android N. So it all

01:20:55.420 --> 01:20:59.640
actually started at a Google I/O
two years ago with Cardboard.

01:20:59.640 --> 01:21:02.360
And since then, Cardboard
has done some pretty amazing

01:21:02.360 --> 01:21:03.170
things.

01:21:03.170 --> 01:21:05.340
There are millions of them
out there in the world,

01:21:05.340 --> 01:21:07.260
in all shapes and sizes.

01:21:07.260 --> 01:21:09.230
We've enabled
thousands of developers

01:21:09.230 --> 01:21:11.500
to build their first VR app.

01:21:11.500 --> 01:21:16.747
And users have installed over 50
million Cardboard-enabled apps.

01:21:16.747 --> 01:21:19.080
We think that's pretty good
for what is, after all, just

01:21:19.080 --> 01:21:20.780
a piece of cardboard.

01:21:20.780 --> 01:21:22.240
Now, we love Cardboard.

01:21:22.240 --> 01:21:24.820
And for us, it represents
so much of what

01:21:24.820 --> 01:21:27.160
we think VR should be about.

01:21:27.160 --> 01:21:28.570
It should be mobile.

01:21:28.570 --> 01:21:29.900
It should be approachable.

01:21:29.900 --> 01:21:31.920
It should be for everyone.

01:21:31.920 --> 01:21:34.270
But we knew it was just
a start, because there's

01:21:34.270 --> 01:21:38.080
a limit to how much you can do,
how immersive an experience you

01:21:38.080 --> 01:21:40.790
can create with some Cardboard
and with phones that were

01:21:40.790 --> 01:21:43.580
really only meant to be phones.

01:21:43.580 --> 01:21:45.130
We wanted to create
something that

01:21:45.130 --> 01:21:47.120
has the best attributes
of Cardboard,

01:21:47.120 --> 01:21:50.800
but which is also comfortable,
richly interactive, and far

01:21:50.800 --> 01:21:52.360
more immersive.

01:21:52.360 --> 01:21:54.280
But to create that
kind of immersion,

01:21:54.280 --> 01:21:57.690
you have to solve-- to make your
brain say, yep, I'm somewhere

01:21:57.690 --> 01:21:59.950
else, you have to solve a
lot of really hard problems

01:21:59.950 --> 01:22:02.614
across all parts of
the VR experience.

01:22:02.614 --> 01:22:04.030
You have to design
a system that's

01:22:04.030 --> 01:22:07.540
capable of rendering at very
high frame rate and resolution.

01:22:07.540 --> 01:22:09.360
To make the experience
really comfortable,

01:22:09.360 --> 01:22:11.310
you have to minimize
what's called motion

01:22:11.310 --> 01:22:12.690
to photon latency.

01:22:12.690 --> 01:22:14.870
That's the delay between
when you move your head

01:22:14.870 --> 01:22:18.020
and when the picture updates
to reflect that motion.

01:22:18.020 --> 01:22:20.710
And you need to solve for how
you interact with things in VR.

01:22:20.710 --> 01:22:23.360
And when you nail
those things, it just

01:22:23.360 --> 01:22:25.570
feels like you're there.

01:22:25.570 --> 01:22:28.440
Well, we've been working
on these problems and more.

01:22:28.440 --> 01:22:31.850
And what we've built won't
be available until this fall.

01:22:31.850 --> 01:22:34.710
But we'd like to
introduce you to it today.

01:22:34.710 --> 01:22:37.710
We call it Daydream.

01:22:37.710 --> 01:22:40.140
Daydream is our platform
for high quality

01:22:40.140 --> 01:22:41.430
mobile virtual reality.

01:22:41.430 --> 01:22:43.310
And in it are all
of the ingredients

01:22:43.310 --> 01:22:47.190
you need to create incredible,
immersive VR experiences.

01:22:47.190 --> 01:22:49.940
Now, over time, Daydream
will encompass VR devices

01:22:49.940 --> 01:22:51.710
in many shapes and sizes.

01:22:51.710 --> 01:22:55.130
But today is about how Daydream
will enable high quality

01:22:55.130 --> 01:22:57.850
VR on Android smartphones.

01:22:57.850 --> 01:23:00.060
And there are three parts
to it-- the smartphones

01:23:00.060 --> 01:23:04.190
themselves, including VR
optimizations to Android N,

01:23:04.190 --> 01:23:07.540
a reference design for a
headset and a controller,

01:23:07.540 --> 01:23:10.670
and apps, both how you get
them, through Google Play,

01:23:10.670 --> 01:23:12.500
and the apps themselves.

01:23:12.500 --> 01:23:15.150
We've designed and built
each part in concert

01:23:15.150 --> 01:23:17.850
with the others, with a
focus on getting the end

01:23:17.850 --> 01:23:20.440
to end user
experience just right.

01:23:20.440 --> 01:23:22.100
So let's start with smartphones.

01:23:22.100 --> 01:23:23.700
Now, the first thing
we did was look

01:23:23.700 --> 01:23:26.400
at what it takes to
build a smartphone that's

01:23:26.400 --> 01:23:28.770
great at being a
smartphone but also

01:23:28.770 --> 01:23:31.490
at being the core
of a VR system.

01:23:31.490 --> 01:23:33.680
And with input from
the major silicon

01:23:33.680 --> 01:23:35.570
vendors and smartphone
manufacturers,

01:23:35.570 --> 01:23:38.940
we've created a set of
phone specifications for VR.

01:23:38.940 --> 01:23:42.810
We call phones that meet
these specs Daydream-ready

01:23:42.810 --> 01:23:45.220
The specs include things
like high performance sensors

01:23:45.220 --> 01:23:48.980
for accurate head tracking,
displays with a fast response

01:23:48.980 --> 01:23:52.220
time to minimize blur and
powerful mobile processors.

01:23:52.220 --> 01:23:53.700
And if a phone
meets these specs,

01:23:53.700 --> 01:23:57.510
it'll be capable of delivering
a great VR experience.

01:23:57.510 --> 01:24:01.070
But the smartphone itself--
it's only part of the story.

01:24:01.070 --> 01:24:03.230
The operating system,
the software--

01:24:03.230 --> 01:24:06.230
it needs to be able to make
use of all these capabilities,

01:24:06.230 --> 01:24:10.010
all while keeping latency
to an absolute minimum.

01:24:10.010 --> 01:24:13.260
So we've introduced what
we call VR Mode as part

01:24:13.260 --> 01:24:17.430
of Android N. We've worked at
all levels of the Android stack

01:24:17.430 --> 01:24:19.320
to optimize it for VR.

01:24:19.320 --> 01:24:22.700
We've focused in particular on
performance and latency, which

01:24:22.700 --> 01:24:26.880
we brought down to
under 20 milliseconds.

01:24:26.880 --> 01:24:30.430
By adding things like single
buffer rendering and VR system

01:24:30.430 --> 01:24:33.910
UI, so notifications and alerts
come through properly in VR.

01:24:33.910 --> 01:24:36.470
And all of this makes for
a really comfortable VR

01:24:36.470 --> 01:24:39.360
experience that we think
users are going to love.

01:24:39.360 --> 01:24:41.850
Now, it's important--
these improvements are

01:24:41.850 --> 01:24:46.070
part of the core of Android
N, so the entire ecosystem

01:24:46.070 --> 01:24:46.980
can benefit.

01:24:46.980 --> 01:24:48.650
What that means
for developers is,

01:24:48.650 --> 01:24:52.440
there are going to be a lot
of Daydream-ready phones.

01:24:52.440 --> 01:24:57.850
In fact, Samsung, Alcatel,
Asus, Huawei, HTC, LG, Xiaomi,

01:24:57.850 --> 01:25:00.550
and ZTE-- all will
have smartphones

01:25:00.550 --> 01:25:02.650
that are compatible with
the Daydream-ready spec,

01:25:02.650 --> 01:25:04.622
and several will be
available this fall.

01:25:10.030 --> 01:25:12.900
So that's phones, with
Daydream-ready phone specs

01:25:12.900 --> 01:25:16.550
and the VR optimizations as
part of Android N. Let's turn

01:25:16.550 --> 01:25:17.940
to headsets.

01:25:17.940 --> 01:25:21.350
Now, this is obvious, but a
VR headset, it's something

01:25:21.350 --> 01:25:24.200
that you wear on your head.

01:25:24.200 --> 01:25:26.340
And because it's
something that you wear,

01:25:26.340 --> 01:25:28.680
there's so many things you
need to get just right.

01:25:28.680 --> 01:25:30.740
It has to have great optics.

01:25:30.740 --> 01:25:31.840
Has to be comfortable.

01:25:31.840 --> 01:25:33.850
The materials need
to feel good, and it

01:25:33.850 --> 01:25:37.260
needs to be really easy
to put on and take off.

01:25:37.260 --> 01:25:39.660
We've taken what we've
learned in all of these areas

01:25:39.660 --> 01:25:41.350
and we've created
a reference design

01:25:41.350 --> 01:25:43.680
for headsets that
will work seamlessly

01:25:43.680 --> 01:25:45.880
with Daydream-ready phones.

01:25:45.880 --> 01:25:48.767
We're sharing this design with
partners across the ecosystem.

01:25:48.767 --> 01:25:50.350
And there'll be
several of them coming

01:25:50.350 --> 01:25:54.600
to market with the first
available this fall.

01:25:54.600 --> 01:25:58.120
Now, when it comes to VR,
everyone thinks about headsets.

01:25:58.120 --> 01:26:01.220
But the controller, how
you interact with VR,

01:26:01.220 --> 01:26:03.176
it's just as important.

01:26:03.176 --> 01:26:04.800
We wanted to create
a Controller that's

01:26:04.800 --> 01:26:08.921
optimized for VR that's
both powerful and intuitive.

01:26:08.921 --> 01:26:11.045
So we've been working on
a controller for Daydream.

01:26:11.045 --> 01:26:12.900
It looks like this.

01:26:12.900 --> 01:26:15.020
And if we actually
zoom in a little bit,

01:26:15.020 --> 01:26:16.480
you can see the
controller itself.

01:26:16.480 --> 01:26:18.180
It's very simple.

01:26:18.180 --> 01:26:20.410
There are a few buttons
and a clickable touchpad,

01:26:20.410 --> 01:26:22.490
so you can scroll and swipe.

01:26:22.490 --> 01:26:25.790
But hidden inside the
controller is the magic.

01:26:25.790 --> 01:26:28.550
We built an orientation
sensor so it knows where it's

01:26:28.550 --> 01:26:30.340
pointing, how it's turning.

01:26:30.340 --> 01:26:32.662
You can do some pretty
awesome things with it.

01:26:32.662 --> 01:26:34.446
Let's have a look.

